  "text": "The Kubernetes admission webhook processing chain consists of two main pipelines: mutating webhooks and validating webhooks. Both follow a similar architectural pattern but with distinct implementation differences.\n\n## Generic Webhook Framework\n\nThe foundation is established in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/admission/plugin/webhook/generic/webhook.go`, which defines the `Webhook` struct. This is an abstract admission plugin that provides common infrastructure for both mutating and validating webhooks. The key methods are:\n\n- `Dispatch()`: Routes webhook calls to the appropriate dispatcher based on admission attributes\n- `ShouldCallHook()`: Determines whether a specific webhook should be invoked by checking namespace selectors, object selectors, rules, and match conditions\n\nThe `generic/interfaces.go` file defines critical abstractions:\n- `Dispatcher`: An interface for dispatching webhook calls to a list of webhooks\n- `Source`: Provides dynamic list of webhooks from configurations\n- `WebhookInvocation`: Describes how to call a webhook, including resource and subresource information\n- `VersionedAttributeAccessor`: Manages versioned attributes for different webhook kinds\n\n## WebhookAccessor Abstraction Layer\n\nIn `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/admission/plugin/webhook/accessors.go`, the `WebhookAccessor` interface provides a unified abstraction for both mutating and validating webhooks. This abstraction allows code to work with either type without type-specific logic. Key implementations include:\n\n- `mutatingWebhookAccessor`: Wraps `v1.MutatingWebhook` objects\n- `validatingWebhookAccessor`: Wraps `v1.ValidatingWebhook` objects\n\nFactory functions `NewMutatingWebhookAccessor` and `NewValidatingWebhookAccessor` create appropriately typed accessors with cached label selectors and compiled match conditions.\n\n## Mutating Webhook Pipeline\n\nThe mutating webhook pipeline starts in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/admission/plugin/webhook/mutating/plugin.go`, where the `Plugin` struct embeds the generic `Webhook`. The `Admit()` method calls the generic `Dispatch()`, which delegates to `mutatingDispatcher`.\n\nThe `mutatingDispatcher` in `dispatcher.go` implements reinvocation logic for mutating webhooks:\n- Uses `webhookReinvokeContext` to track which webhooks have been invoked\n- Implements the `ReinvocationPolicy` mechanism to support re-invocation when mutations occur\n- Processes webhooks serially (one after another) to ensure predictable mutation ordering\n- Applies JSON patches from webhook responses to the object\n- Tracks patch audit annotations for each webhook invocation\n- Supports failure policy (Ignore or Fail)\n\nKey algorithm: The dispatcher iterates through hooks, calls `ShouldCallHook()` for each, and if eligible, calls `callAttrMutatingHook()` which constructs the AdmissionReview, sends it to the webhook endpoint, verifies the response, and applies any patches to the request object.\n\n## Validating Webhook Pipeline\n\nThe validating webhook pipeline starts in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/admission/plugin/webhook/validating/plugin.go`, similar to mutating. However, the `validatingDispatcher` in `dispatcher.go` uses **parallel dispatch** via goroutines:\n\n- Creates a list of relevant hooks by pre-filtering with `ShouldCallHook()`\n- Pre-caches all versioned attributes to avoid repeated conversions\n- Spawns goroutines in a `sync.WaitGroup` for each webhook\n- Each goroutine independently calls its webhook via `callHook()`\n- Collects errors in a channel for centralized error handling\n- Includes panic recovery and crash handling per goroutine\n- Supports failure policy (Ignore or Fail) with independent evaluation per goroutine\n\nThis parallel design improves latency since validating webhooks don't modify the object.\n\n## Configuration Management\n\nThe configuration managers in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/admission/configuration/` serve as the `Source` for webhooks:\n\n- `NewMutatingWebhookConfigurationManager`: Reads `MutatingWebhookConfiguration` objects from a Kubernetes informer, creates `mutatingWebhookAccessor` instances, maintains a cache, and provides sorted lists of webhooks\n- `NewValidatingWebhookConfigurationManager`: Similarly manages `ValidatingWebhookConfiguration` objects\n\nBoth managers implement:\n- Lazy evaluation of webhook configurations\n- Caching of created webhook accessors (expensive due to CEL expression compilation)\n- Event handlers for Add/Update/Delete of configurations\n- Deterministic ordering of webhooks across configurations\n\n## API Type Definitions\n\nIn `admissionregistration/v1/types.go` and `admissionregistration/v1beta1/types.go`, the Kubernetes API defines:\n\n- `MutatingWebhookConfiguration`: A cluster-scoped resource containing multiple `MutatingWebhook` objects. Each webhook specifies rules, failure policy, client configuration, reinvocation policy, side effects, and match conditions.\n- `ValidatingWebhookConfiguration`: A cluster-scoped resource containing multiple `ValidatingWebhook` objects with similar fields but no reinvocation policy.\n- `MutatingWebhook` and `ValidatingWebhook`: Individual webhook specifications with support for namespace/object selectors, rule matching, and CEL-based match conditions.\n\n## Processing Flow Summary\n\n**Mutating Webhooks**:\n1. Plugin.Admit() → Webhook.Dispatch() → mutatingDispatcher.Dispatch()\n2. Serial processing of webhooks (deterministic ordering)\n3. Each webhook may modify the object (patch)\n4. Reinvocation support when objects change\n5. Result: Modified object passed to next plugin\n\n**Validating Webhooks**:\n1. Plugin.Validate() → Webhook.Dispatch() → validatingDispatcher.Dispatch()\n2. Parallel processing of webhooks (spawn goroutines)\n3. Each webhook validates without modification\n4. First error returned (early failure)\n5. Result: Accept/reject decision\n\nBoth pipelines share the same generic webhook matching logic (ShouldCallHook) and WebhookAccessor abstraction, ensuring consistent behavior across mutating and validating webhooks while allowing pipeline-specific optimizations."
